metadata.name: color combinations #171
metadata.description:
the 'color combinations' series was developed as an exercise of combining colors from a single defined palette and the attempt to make all 15 selected colors being able to work within each other.

the constant pursuit for perfectionism made me design more than 200 tentatives of creating a perfect circle, and therefore the circle is the rarest output for the series.

i hope this series serves as a reference and inspire everyone out there.

2,340 possible combinations.
the closer the shape to the circle the rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%.
the bigger the shape the rarer - ranging from 30% to 20%.
beige and black colors are rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%

metadata.name: Urban Flora #70
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Color of life #40
metadata.description:
console.log("Hello world")

After many thoughts about life, about our relationship as individuals in a society I always bring myself the same doubt, does life become only what we do? Or can we, humans, be personalities without being defined by our professions?

This piece comes from this reflection, when I say that I work with art made with code they soon think that I am an unemployed bum. This work represents the colors that in round and elongated shapes abstract my relationship between code and art, putting beauty in continuous lines, and many times confusing in a general context.

PS: Press [S] to save a png :)

metadata.name: Elevation #74
metadata.description:
There’s so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

–

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect’s elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

–

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

–

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: Kinetics #311
metadata.description:
CONTROLS
 * Pause a Kinetic by clicking on the canvas.
 * Increase and decrease the p5js framerate by tapping the left and right arrows.
 * Pause the top layer by tapping down arrow.
 * Save a frame by tapping S.
 * Press H for High Quality, M for Default, L for Low Quality. Note, this effects performance.
 * Reset the Kinetic by by tapping backspace.

Kinetics is a neo-constructivist generative art project built using p5js. Each Kinetic delicately moves from it's origin, giving the appearance of infinite space and possibility. The viewer witnesses the construction of the Kinetic floating inside of the negative. Shapes and lines move around the Kinetic in a dazzling display of contrasting color.

The texture developed for Kinetics, deemed The Creation of the Universe (See top right) is at its core a color gradient of 3 different colors. Each piece construct's itself, drawing lines on top of lines to create a unique self contained assembly of materials as opposed to a realistic abstraction. The Creation of the Universe repeats itself in each piece, just as cells do in an organic structure. From here is where it initially got it's name.

Inspired heavily by the works of Rodchenko and Tatlin, each Kinetic appears to slot together like a puzzle. Each piece has multiple hard edge planes clashing aggressively with each other giving the sense that there is more than just a flat canvas. A quasi realism is created through our desire to build instead of simply paint.

"Long Live Generative Art"

- Mitchell

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #243
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Paper Planes #97
metadata.description:
The joys of childhood are too easily forgotten. Paper Planes is a generative art collection celebrating the joy and magic of origami: from the simplest materials spring delightful forms brimming with ingenuity.

In homage to the handicraft of paper folding, we developed a collection of four pens each with a unique hand-drawn feel: Ink, Pencil, Gel and Dip. They ensure each of our ten origami birds are sketched with subtle imperfections.

Many of the birds are folded from patterned paper based on three traditional Japanese patterns: Seigaiha, Kōjitsunagi and Shippō. Other birds are crafted from block coloured paper which provides pop and contrast whilst sometimes birds match their background, accentuating the hand-drawn strokes that sketched them.

A range of layouts bring each mint to life. Birds can flock and fly across the page. They can be confined to a regimented grid or they can escape and embrace the chaos of the currents. Contrasting frames and borders highlight different colours within each of the 15 handcrafted palettes.

If you're feeling mischievous you can press 'C' in live view to ruffle some feathers…

https://www.phaust.art/paper-planes

----------

In live view, press 'S' to save a high resolution download or add '&size=#' to the end of the URL to render at a custom height.

Original artwork by Phaust. Spring 2022. London / Brighton. Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Sand Shapes #43
metadata.description:
An experiment in line texture by Nate Donato, this piece features lines composed of a sand-like particle texture.  Bounds around line generation properties were set loosely, resulting in many possible line characters with unique weights, wobbles, and more.  Lines are generated in individual layered segments one by one, resulting in a pleasing animation of gradual composition as they compose one of twelve possible shapes, in one of eight possible color schemes.  

Each "line" is made up of thousands of points, and so rendering the live view of this piece may be computer intensive.  As an added bonus a small amount of proprietary line data is emitted to the development console, allowing the minted collection to serve as a palette of potential line qualities for the artist to use in future works.  Any owners of pieces used in this way by the artist on future projects will be granted a share of said future project's royalties.

In active live view, press [1] to view medium res, [2] to view high res, and [0] to return to original viewport width view.

Written in vanilla JavaScript without the use of external libraries.
